.TH BUNPY-UNLINK 1 "2026-04-27" "bunpy" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
bunpy-unlink \- drop registry entries or remove editable links
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B bunpy unlink
.RI [ pkg "...]"
.RB [ \-\-target
.IR dir ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
A bare
.B bunpy unlink
reads
.I ./pyproject.toml
and deletes the JSON entry for the current project from the
global link registry. Existing consumer-side installs keep
working until the consumer re-links or re-installs. Missing
entries are not an error.
.PP
.BI "bunpy unlink " pkg ...
finds the
.IB name - version .dist-info
directory under the target, verifies it carries
.B INSTALLER=bunpy-link
(so the verb never accidentally removes a pinned wheel), walks
.B RECORD
with the same path-escape guard
.BR bunpy-remove (1)
uses, and unlinks every listed file. The dist-info directory is
then removed. A name that has no link installed prints
.RI ' "no link for " name '
and exits 0.
.PP
After
.B bunpy unlink <pkg>
you can run
.B bunpy install
to re-fetch the pinned wheel and put it back in place.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-\-target " dir"
Consumer-side site-packages target. Defaults to
.IR ./.bunpy/site-packages .
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B BUNPY_LINK_DIR
Override the registry root. See
.BR bunpy-link (1).
.SH EXIT STATUS
Zero on a clean unregister or unlink. Non-zero on a missing
.BR pyproject.toml ,
a missing project name, or an unwritable target.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR bunpy-link (1),
.BR bunpy-remove (1),
.BR bunpy-install (1),
.BR bunpy (1).
